Fifth Step:
\begin{align*} 
&amp;\text{For the pair } (1,8): 18x0,18x1,\dots,18x9 \implies\text{ only } 108, 138, 168, 198\text{ are divisible by } 27.\\ 
&amp;\text{For the pair } (2,7): 27x0,27x1,\dots,27x9 \implies \text{ none of these are divisible by } 27. \\ 
&amp;\text{For the pair } (3,6): 36x0,36x1,\dots,36x9 \implies \text{ only } 360\text{ is divisible by } 27.\\ 
&amp;\text{For the pair } (4,5): 45x0,45x1,\dots,45x9 \implies \text{ none of these are divisible by } 27.\\ 
&amp;\text{For the pair } (5,4) \text{ and } (8,1) \text{ we can deduce in a similar fashion.}
\end{align*} 
There are $5$ possible tens and units digits that add up to 9 and the number must be even. Out of the $5$ possible combinations $(1, 8), (2, 7),$ $(3, 6),(4, 5),$ and $(7,2)$  we found out $(1, 8)$ and $(3, 6)$  satisfy the conditions of being divisible by 27, that makes two.

